---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import { HF_TABLE, MF_TABLE, ECDSA_TABLE, MID_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The cryptographic toolkit"
  description="Hashes, MACs, signatures, one-way chains and Merkle trees — the primitives OSNMA is built from."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="1 · Cryptographic foundations"
    title="The cryptographic toolkit"
    lead="OSNMA combines five well-understood primitives. Meet each one before seeing how they snap together."
  />

  <h2>Hash functions</h2>
  <p>
    A cryptographic hash <Formula tex="x = H(m)" /> turns any message into a
    fixed-size fingerprint. It is <strong>one-way</strong> (given <Formula tex="x" />
    you cannot find <Formula tex="m" />) and <strong>collision resistant</strong>
    (you cannot find two messages with the same fingerprint). OSNMA uses SHA-256,
    with SHA3-256 reserved as an option <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.2.3.4" />.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={HF_TABLE} />

  <h2>Message Authentication Codes (MACs)</h2>
  <p>
    A MAC is a keyed fingerprint: <Formula tex="t = \mathrm{MAC}(K, m)" />. Anyone
    holding the secret key <Formula tex="K" /> can compute or check the tag
    <Formula tex="t" />, proving the message was produced by a key-holder and not
    altered. MACs are fast and short — ideal for a low-rate broadcast. OSNMA uses
    HMAC-SHA-256 or CMAC-AES <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.2.3.5" />.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={MF_TABLE} />
  <Callout type="warning" title="The broadcast key-distribution problem">
    <p>
      MACs are symmetric: verifying requires the same secret used to sign. In a
      one-to-many broadcast, handing that secret to every receiver would let any of
      them forge messages. This is exactly the impasse TESLA breaks.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Digital signatures</h2>
  <p>
    Signatures are asymmetric: a private key signs, and a freely shared public key
    verifies. No secret is shared with verifiers, so no verifier can forge. The
    price is size and cost — signatures are far larger than MAC tags. OSNMA uses
    ECDSA over P-256 or P-521 <DocRef doc="icd" section="6.1.1" />.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={ECDSA_TABLE} />
  <p>
    OSNMA uses signatures sparingly — once, to authenticate the root of a key chain
    — and then relies on cheap MACs for the high-rate traffic. Best of both worlds.
  </p>

  <h2>One-way (hash) chains</h2>
  <p>
    Apply a hash repeatedly and you get a chain in which each link is the hash of
    the next:
  </p>
  <Formula tex="K_i = H(K_{i+1})" display />
  <p>
    From a disclosed key you can walk <em>backward</em> toward the start in a single
    step each, but you can never walk <em>forward</em> to predict an
    as-yet-undisclosed key. Publish the first link <Formula tex="K_0" /> as a trusted
    anchor, and anyone can later confirm that a freshly revealed
    <Formula tex="K_i" /> belongs to the chain by hashing it back down to
    <Formula tex="K_0" />. This asymmetry is the backbone of TESLA.
  </p>

  <h2>Merkle trees</h2>
  <p>
    A Merkle tree commits to many items with a single hash. Each leaf is hashed,
    each internal node hashes its two children, and the single <strong>root</strong>
    depends on every leaf. To prove one leaf belongs to the tree you reveal just
    that leaf and the sibling node at each level — a short path — and the verifier
    recomputes the root. OSNMA uses a 16-leaf SHA-256 tree to authenticate its
    public keys <DocRef doc="icd" section="6.2" />.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can watch this happen on real data in the
    <a href={withBase('/machinery/merkle-tree')}>Merkle Tree Explorer</a>.
  </p>
  <div class="level-engineer">
    <p>
      Each public-key message (DSM-PKR) carries one leaf plus the four siblings
      needed to climb to the root, selected by the MID field:
    </p>
    <ValueTable table={MID_TABLE} />
  </div>

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      Keep these five in mind: hashes fingerprint, MACs authenticate cheaply with a
      shared key, signatures authenticate without sharing a secret, one-way chains
      let a key be trusted after the fact, and Merkle trees authenticate many keys
      with one root. The next page assembles them into TESLA.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
